SIMPLE: flippant
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flippant
<hw>Flip"pant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Prov. E.
<ets>flip</ets> to move nimbly; cf. W. <ets>llipa</ets> soft, limber,
pliant, or Icel. <ets>fleipa</ets> to babble, prattle. Cf.
<er>Flip</er>, <er>Fillip</er>, <er>Flap</er>, <er>Flipper</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Of smooth, fluent, and rapid speech; speaking with ease
and rapidity; having a voluble tongue; talkative.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It becometh good men, in such cases, to be <qex>flippant</qex> and
free in their speech.</q> <rj><qau>Barrow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Speaking fluently and confidently, without knowledge
or consideration; empty; trifling; inconsiderate; pert; petulant.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Flippant</xex> epilogues.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Thomson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To put <qex>flippant</qex> scorn to the blush.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A sort of <qex>flippant</qex>, vain discourse.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flippant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flippant
<hw>Flip"pant</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A flippant person.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flippantly</ent>⟦br⟧
